        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9453.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. L. Brunton, 11 May 1874</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Brunton’s reply to CD’s letter of 11 May 1874 has not been found. CD’s questions were about the microscopic appearance of milk, and the digestion of milk by <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi> (sundew).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9453.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. L. Brunton, 11 May 1874</ref> and n. 1, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, p. 114.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6370.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Samuel William Moore</ref>; for CD’s and Brunton’s experiments with pepsin, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, pp. 123–4.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">In his response to CD’s letter of 11 May 1874, Brunton had evidently mentioned the digestive properties of the juice of the papaw fruit (<hi rend="italic">Carica papaya</hi>). Brunton described the digestive action of the ferment derived from the fruit (papain) in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1009.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Brunton 1885</ref>, pp. 777–8.</note>
        </div>        
            
